@mrdoob I previously skimmed the paper, and I believe there was some discussion regarding the importance of selecting the correct color space in which to dither. (i.e., linear space or gamma-corrected space), but I haven't studied the paper carefully.

Now that you mention it, I wonder why `<encodings_fragment>` is not after `<fog_fragment>`... ?  /ping @bhouston I assume `fog` color is in linear space, like other colors...

Here is a guess, but there likely is no correct answer.

	#include <tonemapping_fragment>
	#include <fog_fragment>
	#include <dithering_fragment>
	#include <encodings_fragment>
	#include <premultiplied_alpha_fragment>

My preference is this:
```
#include <tonemapping_fragment>
#include <encodings_fragment>
#include <fog_fragment> // Fog color is in output color space so you can blend to clear color
#include <premultiplied_alpha_fragment> // must be after encoding to prevent artifacts
#include <dithering_fragment> // must ditther the output color in its current bit depth.
```

But I haven't tested it.  Fog right now is assumed to be in output space (whatever that is) because often people clear a buffer with a color and then set that color to be the fog color and expect their render to blend to match that clear color.  Thus fog should be in "output space" until we support auto-tone mapping the clear colors.  Fog needs to be after tone mapping and encoding.

I believe that dithering should be at the end because it will accurately represent the resulting floating points colors that these produce.  Dithering is a method of converting an region of output color to a reduced bitspace output color while presenting the original average color before the bit space reduction.  Thus it needs to run on final color, not a intermediate color.

I haven't read the code for dithering yet, and thus I am not sure whether it is compatible with pre and post-multipled alpha colors.  If it is not yet compatible with pre-multiplied alpha it needs to be moved before the premultipled alpha fragment, or it needs to be made to be compatible with pre-multiplied alpha.

@WestLangley moved "premultiplied-alpha-fragment" to the end from the front, but didn't specify why.  He doesn't provide a reasoning, but I assume he saw this commit of mine here from a couple days ago: https://github.com/bhouston/three.js/commit/125fa1dc7f23ae22a84bb81dafa9d07c2bfdb76d  Basically in some cases, there are issues with alpha blended transparency in pre-multipled alpha rendering. 
 Moving this fragment to the end corrects these issues.

Maybe something like this is a bit better:
```
#include <tonemapping_fragment>
#include <color_correction_fragment> // does only-monotonic color space conversion
#include <fog_fragment> // Fog color is in output color space so you can blend to clear color
#include <premultiplied_alpha_fragment> // must be after encoding to prevent artifacts
#include <dithering_fragment> // must ditther the output color in its current bit depth.
#include <encodings_fragment> // does conversion to non-monotonic
```

If we split color space conversion from the encodings, we could do the above.  It would be more flexible and clear.  We could also support LUTs in the color space conversions as well.

@bhouston said

>If we split color space conversion from the encodings... each texture and render target should have both a ColorSpace (Linear, sRGB, AdobeRGB, Gamma20, Gamma22) and a Encoding (None, RGBE, RGBM, RGBD, LogLUV, CMYK) parameter.

I do like that idea, conceptually. However, I'm not sure all ColorSpace/Encoding combinations make sense. Maybe that is not a big deal, though...
